### Description

@jeromelaban of Uno project suggested to report this bug here because  "This definitely seems like a runtime bug then...  This is an unrelated [to UnoPlatform] error, which likely means that the issue has not been fixed in the runtime."  Initially, it was suggested that this was some "code has been removed by the linker"  - but testing has probably ruled that out.

**ISSUE:**
On a WASM client, an "Uncaught ExitStatus ExitStatus" is encountered when an Interface exposes a [default interface method](https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/language-reference/proposals/csharp-8.0/default-interface-methods) - but it works fine as part of the WinUI3 client.   In my particular case, the Interface is contained within a net6.0 library that is referenced in the WASM/WinUI projects.  The error seems to happen just as you try to enter the function that references any class which implements the Interface (i.e. no event logs are written inside the function).  See the code sample in below:


**PREVIOUS RELATED DISCUSSION**
This issue was first encountered in our project when we were calling the  XmlSerializer to create an instance of a class that implemented a Interface with a default method.  Originally, it was thought to be an issue with the XmlSerializer and previous discussion occurred on the topic: ["Uncaught ExitStatus ExitStatus" Encountered Instantiating new XmlSerializer() [WASM] #10071](https://github.com/unoplatform/uno/discussions/10071).   However, we were able to rule out XmlSerializer because directly instantiating the class causes the "Uncaught ExitStatus ExitStatus" issue to happen.  Also, removing the default method code from the Interface and placing it inside the derriced class does not cause a the problem.


### Reproduction Steps

```
namespace MyProject.Models;

/// <summary>
/// DEBUG ONLY : This is a vastly simplified mock-up of the SimulationResult class used to isolate the conditions 
/// which causes the "Uncaught ExitStatus ExitStatus" issue.  The MOCK/SAMPLE values are for illustration only.
/// </summary>
public interface IMockInterface<D, R> : IDomainBounds<D>, IRangeBounds<R>, IEquatable<IDomainRangeBounds<D, R>>
    where D : IComparable
    where R : IComparable
{
    /****************************************************************************************************************
     *  The "Uncaught ExitStatus ExitStatus" issue occurs when this method is uncommented, and Equals() is invoked  *
     *  as a default interface method.   However, if the Equals() method is moved to the derrived class, then the   *
     *  "Uncaught ExitStatus ExitStatus" issue is not observed & all test cases are performed successfully          *
     ****************************************************************************************************************/
    //bool IEquatable<IDomainRangeBounds<D, R>>.Equals(IDomainRangeBounds<D, R> other)
    //{
    //    return Equals((other as IDomainBounds<D>)) && Equals(other as IRangeBounds<R>);
    //}

}


/// <summary>
/// DEBUG ONLY : This is a vastly simplified mock-up of the SimulationResult class used to isolate the conditions 
/// which causes the "Uncaught ExitStatus ExitStatus" issue.  The MOCK/SAMPLE values are for illustration only.
/// </summary>
public class SimulationResult_TEST : SimulationResult_Core, IMockInterface<DateOnly, double>
{
    public DateOnly MinDomain {
        get {
            return DateOnly.MinValue;
        }
    }

    public DateOnly MaxDomain {
        get {
            return DateOnly.MaxValue;
        }
    }

    public double MinRange {
        get {
            return double.MinValue;
        }
    }

    public double MaxRange {
        get {
            return double.MaxValue;
        }
    }

    /****************************************************************************************************************
     *  SEE COMMENT ABOVE REGARDING Equals() used as a default interface method                                     *
     ****************************************************************************************************************/
    public bool Equals(IDomainRangeBounds<DateOnly, double> other)
    {
         return Equals((other as IDomainBounds<D>)) && Equals(other as IRangeBounds<R>);
    }

}

```

### Expected behavior

Both the WinUI & WASM clients should execute the [default interface method](https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/language-reference/proposals/csharp-8.0/default-interface-methods) in exactly the same way.

### Actual behavior

Using Uno.WASM.Bootstrapper (version="7.0.0-dev.218") I observe the "Uncaught ExitStatus ExitStatus" message, with new "mono_wasm_stringify" bit at the top.  When this happens, no catchable exception is thrown & the tread just seeming to end.

