The general problem is that the csproj contains all sorts of files. Some of them are C# that should be passed to compiler and not copied to the output, some are server side configuration files, like appSettings.json which may contain secrets. They are all part of `<Content />` collection as well. So there needs to be a pattern for expressing files that are meant to be accessible from the browser. In the proprietary runtime SDK (WasmAppBuilder), it was the `WasmExtraFilesToDeploy`. AspNetCore (and Blazor and now the more general WasmSDK) has convention of wwwroot. All Content items marked with CopyToOutput are copied to output, but not to the output/wwwroot, because they are  not treated as browser-accessible files.

The gitignore can contain various patterns, so that wwwroot can contain user files as well as generated files. Anyway I understand the inconvenience.

@javiercn might have more context about generated files accessible from the server.

